description:
Large reasoning models (LRMs) typically improve performance in complex tasks by generating long-chain-of-thoughts. However, this "freely expandable reasoning" often leads to redundant reasoning paths, structural instability, and wasted computational resources. Existing methods mostly address length constraints or external rewards, lacking optimization modeling of the "reasoning structure itself."  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training and tuning paradigm: Assignment-Governed Reasoning (AGR). This paradigm introduces the classic **Assignment Problem** into reasoning trajectory modeling for the first time, formalizing the relationship between "reasoning steps" and "implicit reasoning requirements/sub-goals" as a dynamic bipartite graph matching problem. By constructing a cost matrix, optimal matching constraints, and a differentiable relaxation optimization process, the model learns that "each step of reasoning must serve a specific sub-goal," thus achieving structured reasoning alignment.  
 &nbsp; 
  AGR not only changes the reasoning generation method but also reconstructs the source of LRM training signals, shifting it from "sequence generation learning" to "globally optimal matching learning." This method is theoretically equivalent to solving the dynamic assignment optimization problem in the reasoning space, thereby significantly improving reasoning efficiency and structural compactness.

